n assertion of medical control, this work positions managerial medicine as a co-constructed venture. Although driven by different motives, doctors, nurses, professional bodies, government agencies and international organisations were all integral to the creation of managerial systems, working within a context of considerable professional, political, technological, economic and cultural change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDiabetesxTreatmentzGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aMedical carezGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aMedical policyzGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh  aAccountability.  aChronic disease.  aDiabetes.  aHealth care bureaucracy.  aManaged medicine.  aNational Health Service.  aPost-war Britain.  aPreventive medicine.  aProfessionalisation.  aRisk.  ageneral practice.  amedical professionalism.1 aMoore, Martin D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2019 eBook-Packagez978311128249740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781526113092zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526113092zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526113092/original  a978-3-11-128249-7 Manchester University Press 2019 eBook-Packageb2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA